Yeah, 12,000 kg doesn't sound too out there. The biggest problem with both the F-Heavy and indeed any Saturn-V equivalent like the BFR is that the trip duration at a suitable payload is not pleasant for a manned mission. It was quite acceptable for the MSL mission to take nine months to get there, but as soon as people are on board you either need a very short trip, or a massive payload to fit all the stuff you need to keep them mentally and physically healthy. Quite aside from the machinery needed to deal with microgravity for that long, interplanetary space is radioactive as fuck, yo. One of the early mission objectives on the SLS program is to do a long shot around the outside of the moon and break into the region where the sun dominates with a dummy crew module packed with sensors to get an initial sense of what we need to design against, where hotspots appear in the cabin, etc.

Aerobraking is a useable strategy on Mars, but unfortunately while the thinness makes reentry much more forgiving, it also means aerobraked landings are basically a non-starter for anything but a tiny payload. Curiosity was under a ton, but even with the most aggressive possible aerobraking (that is, hot re-entry), plus a supersonic parachute, it needed some significant retro-thrust to make a safe landing. A crew vessel can use aerobraking for orbital capture, maybe, but you're going to need retro-thrust for the actual landing; IIRC SpaceX's own tentative Martian landing strategies involve using bigass rocket motors to stop you cratering.

Part of the appeal of remotely constructing as much of a base as possible is it gives us the maximum time to develop engines for the crew vehicles.
